<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-329-737  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 329 737.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Feb 13 1989 v23 n6 p89(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Managing the virus threat. (MIS measures against computer viruses)(In Depth)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McAfee, John D.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer viruses have emerged as a serious threat to MIS managers,with a measurable impact in terms of lost money, man-hours andcomputing resources.andP;  Traditional methods of data protection aremostly ineffective against today's viruses.andP;  Viruses appear in avariety of forms, some small and compact, while others aresignificant constructs consisting of thousands of instructions.andO;Viruses enter corporate installations via various interfaces: froman infected diskette from an outside source, through acquisitionof infected machines, and through electronic communications.andP;  Theinfection process occurs in four stages: local memory, local diskstorage, shared-file system and infection of systemwide removablestorage.andP;  The most effective way to prevent virus infection is toprohibit the use of public-domain and shareware software programs,in addition to using infection-prevention products.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer virusesMISData SecurityMethodsInformation Resource ManagementPreventive Maintenance.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphcharttable.andO;Caption:   The computer virus epidemic spreads. (graph)Four stages of viral infection. (chart)The most common computer viruses. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>